  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. Key requirements typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying regulatory authorities about potential money laundering\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing Anti-Money Laundering (AML) programs\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n- Training employees on detection methods\n\n4. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction documentation\n- Preserving customer identification records\n- Developing audit trails\n\n5. Risk Management\n- Implementing internal controls\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Conducting ongoing transaction monitoring\n\n6. Potential Penalties\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and protect the integrity of the financial system.",
